,Recommended,241410,8361456,"Posted: 28 December, 2013",all,snargleplax,"Blending 2D tower defense gameplay with catapult physics, this game feels like a cross between Tower Wars and Angry Birds (there are even some none-too-sly ""angry"" references in the game).  Like Tower Wars, CastleStorm expands the basic tower defense formula by giving each opponent a citadel to defend and troops to send against the other.In addition to sending troops, you can also fire various forms of ammunition, ballista/catapult style, against the opposing troops and their fortress.  By taking out sections of the fortress, you diminish the enemy's capabilities.  The physics involved are absolutely reminiscent of Angry Birds, and there's a great deal of satisfaction when you finally knock out that last section of wall and watch a huge tower come crashing down.This game had a lot of elements I was looking for.  As of this review, I've played just four hours of the campaign (about 2/3 through), and haven't played around with the fortress design mechanics or anything -- they look good, though, as does multiplayer (assuming one can find an opponent).  The cutscenes are hokey in the extreme, but I'm not finding myself annoyed by them -- it's just a bit of popcorn to tie the missions together, and it works fine.Definitely a good buy (especially on sale) for fans of tower defense, physics games, and artillery games (e.g. Scorched Earth, Worms, etc.).  Happy to see more games moving in this direction, moving past the basics of a single genre.  Probably the biggest downside for me is that the pacing tends to be a bit frantic, not leaving much room to contemplate one's strategy."
