76561198056096151,Recommended,241410,8771825,"Posted: 19 January, 2014",all,Your Tovarisch Uncle Joey,"CastleStorm was a game I picked up on sale for roughly £3 it was a real steal, never hearing of the game before, I watched TotalBiscuit's review, seeing his only major problem was the inability to create castles from the ground up (his fault due to him not seeing the ""clear castle button"") I picked it up.What do I think of the game?+Cartoon style, both in dialogue and in graphics, the games fantasy setting creates an opportunity for great light-hearted dialogue, from breaking the fourth wall, tongue in cheek humour and references, the atmosphere of the game is a refreshing change from the dark fantasy style we have been getting for so long, the enemies rrange from pretentious archers and cowardly soldiers to Boxing Golems and Idiotic Trolls. The game is lovingly wonderful (and isn't that just a bit sappy?)+ Strong gameplay, the game seamlessy combines spells, RTS and catapaulting together, the catapults vast array of weapons (from boulders, to conversion potions and homing exlpopding eagles) are bound to the left mouse button, the spells (summoning your hero for a direct control fight or summoning holy swords to implae your enemies) to the middle mouse button and your troops (catapult launching gluttons, pladins and donkey riders and more) to the right button, each form of combat featuring a hotkey and keyboard select system allowing for seamless combination of the trio)+ Destruction physics, speaks for itself really, nothing more satisfying then watching your ballista strike a javelin through your enemy or rocks smashing into the opponents castle and crumbling it away or even bouncing a battering ram sheep into the gate. It works great, and aside from the occasional glitched miss, its fluid, effective and satisfying, being the core part of the game it should be and certainly is.- Friendly Fire, I don't know who thought this was a good idea, so heres the situation, your troops are weakened by the oncoming plaadin, you fire your ballista straight for his head to give your troops a break, instead it gets sent smacking into your soldiers back and he dies, the enemies gain ground while you sent another squad to retake the ground you lost. Theres the problem, its almost impossible to use the troops and ballistae in tandem, they always get in the way of each other, there is no point using the infantry because despite the infantry being effective the ballistae is more effective and when your troops are LITERALLY BLOCKING shots for you're enemy, whats the point? putting in friendly fire just brickwalls the infantry and stops the fun, in a game like this, the realism of the firendly fire is all the more annoying.- Castle editor is pointless, don't get me wrong, its fun and all, putting your castle into action and creating an unstoppable design, but when the preset ones are already there, made by professionals, completely balanced, and tested for the most efficiency, theres no point in building your own where theres certain to be a gaping hole in your defense or not enough space for a troopers barracks etc. its the same problem as littlebigplanet, the created levels are fun but the ones made by proffessionals are almost certain to be better, less buggy and of a higher quality.Overview: despie its huge flaw of friendly fire, its good to remember it is the only serious flaw, and the editor is still there for those who want to tinker and the architects in us that could make great castles, so its more of a personal gripe but i think others would see the same thing, but that said its still a completely functuntional feature, so for its excellent features, great and realised ideas and wonderfully cheesy story, castlestorm gets a 9 out of 10, its only £7 and thats the price of most dlc for triple A games, which i guarantee you will probably won't be worth it, so give castlestorm a try, Its worth every penny"
